    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-22T08:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-22T08:35:00-05:00" n="482"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.6363/9–2244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-22T17:00:00+03:25"
                            >September 22, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 22—1:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>701. The Prime Minister last night told me that the principal object of the
                    Kavtaradze Commission concerned the petroleum fields in the north mentioned in
                    my telegram 698, September 21. He said, however, there were other questions
                    which would be explored concerning the economic and commercial relations between
                    Russia and Iran. He added the interesting comment that he would broach to
                    Kavtaradze the subject of the withdrawal of Russian armed forces and endeavor to
                    explain [<hi rend="italic">explore?</hi>] the mind of Moscow if possible towards
                    this subject and would suggest that the Russians should make preparations for
                    withdrawal within the near future. The Prime Minister was not pessimistic [<hi
                        rend="italic">optimistic?</hi>] about withdrawal but said he thought it was
                    a good opportunity to show interest in this subject of prime importance.</p>
                <p>Dr. Millspaugh has heard that the commission is here to settle some outstanding
                    commercial accounts as one of its secondary interests.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
